card sales are included in *Cost of revenue*. Taxes collected and remitted to governments are excluded from the transaction price. Sales commissions with an amortization period of one year or less are expensed as incurred within *Selling, general, and administrative (SG&A)* expenses.\n\n### 3. Cost Capitalization\n*   **PP&E Enhancements:** Costs for significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase an asset's functionality, output, or expected life are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n*   **Satellites:** Capitalized costs include the costs to build the satellites (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as launch costs incurred by the Space segment to get them to orbit (including an allocation of the flight vehicle).\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** Interest is capitalized during the construction period for significant long-term projects (e.g., AI infrastructure data centers and launch facilities). Capitalization begins when preparation activities commence, is calculated using average accumulated expenditures and a weighted average borrowing rate, and ceases when portions are substantially completed. Capitalized interest becomes part of the asset's historical cost.\n*   **Construction in Progress (CIP):** Includes ongoing construction and expansion of facilities, equipment, and AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service.\n*   **Starship Development:** Because Starship is currently in the development stage, a majority of its costs are expensed to *Research and development* as incurred rather than capitalized.\n\n### 4. Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E)\n*   **Aerospace Asset Classification:**\n    *   **Reusable (PP&E):** Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy boosters (first stages), fairings, Merlin engines, and fully reusable Dragon capsules.\n    *   **Expendable (Inventory):** Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy second stages.\n*   **Valuation & Depreciation Methods:** PP&E is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation. \n    *   *Standard Assets:* Depreciated using the straight-line method over estimated useful lives.\n    *   *Flight Vehicles & Spacecraft:* Depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights**. Management estimates this by considering recovery/refurbishment success rates, economics, customer acceptance limits, mission manifests, and retirement timing (e.g., transitioning from Falcon to Starship).\n    *   *Satellites:* Depreciation factors in on-orbit performance, orbit-raise timing, service capability, and constellation evolution.\n    *   *Leasehold Improvements:* Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n    *   *Adjustments:* If useful lives or expected remaining flights change, the depreciation rate is adjusted prospectively.\n*   **Estimated Useful Lives Schedule:**\n    *   Servers and networking equipment: 5 - 6 years\n    *   Satellites: 3 - 5 years\n    *   Machinery and equipment: 3 - 10 years\n    *   Flight vehicle hardware: 5 - 25 flights\n    *   Data center infrastructure: 20 - 25 years\n    *   Launch sites: 7 - 20 years\n    *   Buildings and improvements: 30 years\n    *   Leasehold improvements: Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease\n*   **Impairment & Disposals:**\n    *   Evaluated at the lowest level of independent cash flows whenever events indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological changes, negative trends, or changes in asset use).\n    *   If carrying value exceeds estimated fair value, an impairment charge is recognized.\n    *   *Routine* disposals, scrapping, gateway decommissions, and recurring operational losses are charged to *Cost of revenue* or *SG&A*.\n    *   *Abnormal* impairments (outside the normal course of business) are charged to *Impairment* (e.g., a $24 million write-off of damaged flight vehicles in the Space segment in Q1 2025).",
