2026-06-09 20:27:15,581 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Accounting-Policy Question for Orbital AI Compute Satellites\n\n### The Core Question: Segment Asset Attribution and Cost Allocation\n\nOnce manufacturing of orbital AI compute satellites begins, the central accounting-policy question is: **Which reportable segment should capitalize, own, and depreciate these assets, given that their manufacturing, deployment, and operation draw on resources and capabilities from all three segments?**\n\nThis question arises because orbital AI compute satellites are inherently cross-segment assets:\n\n| Input Source | Segment | Contribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Manufacturing facilities** | Connectivity / Space | Bastrop, TX facility (a Connectivity/Space manufacturing hub) is expanding in 2026 to produce AI compute satellites; Redmond, WA produces satellite buses |\n| **Satellite platform** | Connectivity | V3 platform architecture, inter-satellite laser mesh network, fleet-management software |\n| **Launch services** | Space | Starship deployment (up to 60 V3 satellites per launch) |\n| **AI compute payload** | AI | AI accelerators replacing communications hardware, custom silicon (Terafab initiative), Grok model operations |\n| **Thermal / power systems** | Shared | Substantially larger radiators and solar arrays (~100 kW per metric ton) unique to AI compute variant |\n\nThe filing does **not** disclose an accounting policy that resolves how an asset spanning all three segments\' functional domains should be attributed for segment reporting purposes.\n\n---\n\n### Most Relevant Disclosed Policies\n\n**1. Inter-Segment Transaction Elimination Policy**\n- The company does **not** recognize inter-segment revenue. When the Space segment launches internal payloads, no revenue is recorded; instead, launch costs (including an allocation of the flight vehicle) are **capitalized as satellites in PP&E** on the consolidated balance sheet of the receiving segment.\n- *Relevance:* This policy governs how the Space segment\'s launch contribution to orbital AI compute deployment would be recorded—but it does not address which segment is the "receiving segment" when the asset serves AI compute rather than connectivity.\n\n**2. Satellite Cost Capitalization Policy**\n- Capitalized satellite costs include **parts, labor, allocated overhead, and launch costs** (including an allocation of the flight vehicle). These are recorded within *Property, plant, and equipment, net*.\n- *Relevance:* Manufacturing at Bastrop and Redmond would generate costs that must be accumulated and capitalized—but the policy does not specify which segment\'s capital expenditure line these costs flow through during construction.\n\n**3. PP&E Classification and Depreciation Policies**\n- The filing discloses materially different useful lives for asset categories that orbital AI compute satellites straddle:\n  - **Satellites:** 3–5 years\n  - **Servers and networking equipment:** 5–6 years\n  - **Data center infrastructure:** 20–25 years\n- Flight vehicles and spacecraft are depreciated based on **expected number of average flights** rather than straight-line time.\n- *Relevance:* Orbital AI compute satellites are described as "orbital data centers" and "modular orbital AI compute shells"—functionally flying data centers. The filing does not specify whether these would be depreciated as satellites (3–5 years), as data center infrastructure (20–25 years), or under some hybrid methodology. This choice would have a material impact on segment-level depreciation expense and Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n**4. Shared Cost and Overhead Allocation**\n- Cost of revenue includes **allocated overhead** and **infrastructure costs** (shared manufacturing facilities, data center costs). The MD&A references year-over-year changes in allocated G&A overhead across segments (e.g., a $52 million decrease in 2025, a $54 million increase to Connectivity in 2024), but the **specific allocation methodology is not disclosed**.\n- *Relevance:* Shared manufacturing lines at Bastrop producing both Starlink Kits and AI compute satellites would require a cost-allocation methodology that the filing does not currently describe.\n\n**5. Segment Reporting Framework**\n- The CODM (CEO) evaluates segments based on **segment income (loss) from operations** and Segment Adjusted EBITDA (which adds back depreciation, share-based compensation, restructuring, and impairments). The filing states the CODM **does not evaluate segments using [total assets]** (sentence truncated but consistent with standard ASC 280 disclosure).\n- *Relevance:* Because the CODM does not review segment-level assets, the attribution of orbital AI compute satellite PP&E to a specific segment may not be visible in segment reporting—yet the depreciation flowing through that segment\'s income from operations would directly affect Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n---\n\n### Why This Is Materially Unresolved\n\nThe filing explicitly notes **"material differences between connectivity satellites and AI compute satellites,"** including the removal of communications hardware and the addition of AI accelerators, larger radiators, and significantly larger solar arrays. This suggests these are **distinct asset classes**, not minor variants of existing Starlink satellites. Yet the current accounting policies were designed for a paradigm in which:\n\n- Satellites serve a single purpose (connectivity)\n- The receiving segment is unambiguous (Connectivity)\n- Depreciation follows the satellite useful-life schedule (3–5 years)\n\nOnce manufacturing begins (Bastrop expansion in 2026; deployment expected as early as 2028), the company will need to establish and disclose:\n\n1. **Segment attribution policy** for assets manufactured by one segment, launched by another, and operated by a third\n2. **Depreciation methodology** for orbital compute infrastructure that functionally serves as a data center but physically operates as a satellite\n3. **Cost-allocation methodology** for shared manufacturing facilities producing both connectivity and AI compute hardware\n\nThe filing does not provide sufficient information to conclude how these questions will be resolved.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
